> s

> s

You are in a nursery.
You can see a dollhouse, Birgitta and a carriage.
You can go north.
You recognize this room, it's Polly's nursery.  You couldn't count the happy hours that you spent here -- attending fancy tea parties with the other dolls, happily baking imaginary cakes in Polly's play oven, or just tidying the family rooms of Polly's giant dollhouse!  Now the nursery seems oddly quiet and still, the floor covered in a thick film of dust, the walls festooned with great gobs of cobwebs. A faded mural on the southern wall depicts a circus scene, jolly clowns and graceful acrobats and striking tigers cavorting in front of a rainbow-colored big top tent. You still see a few toys that you recognize, including Polly's old dollhouse, now broken and splintered, and, lying on the floor, your fellow doll Birgitta.

There are scuff marks in the dust that look like footprints.
> x footprints

> x footprints
The dust in the middle of the room has been disturbed, almost as if there was a violent scuffle. A line of small footprints leads from the middle of the room to the door.
> x Birgitta

> x Birgitta
My word, it's Bergitta!  You remember her well.  She is...was... another one of the dolls in the nursery.  Yet here she is, lying on the floor in a heap, her limbs tangled, her eyes closed.  Is she... asleep? Dolls do sometimes sort of sleep; when Polly tucked you into your doll bed, you did go to sleep in a fashion.  But dolls don't sleep in the way that humans do.  You don't lose yourself to unconsciousness, you don't descend into dreams.

"Gita? Is that you?" you ask, a slight quiver in your voice.  Hesitantly, you poke at Gita with your hand.  She doesn't respond.

You gasp in confusion.  What's going on? Is Gita dead? That can't be! A doll can't die as along as she's nurtured by the love of a child.  If Gita is gone, that must mean... where is Polly?

But if... heaven forbid...if Polly is gone... how is it that you're still here?  A cold shiver runs through your stuffing.

> x dollhouse

> x dollhouse
You remember Polly's aunt brought her back this dollhouse when she went on vacation to England; it's a large Nuremberg dollhouse, just four rooms -- a bedroom, living room, bath, and kitchen. Polly used to make you and Gita and Juliette play house in this dollhouse, alternatively baking imaginary bread in the kitchen, doing chores in the living room, or just sleeping in the bedroom.  The dollhouse has since collapsed in on itself; it's now little more than a pile of splinters, although the house's facade is still relatively intact.
> x facade

> x facade
The front of the dollhouse is still in one piece, lying on the floor.  It's a large flat plank of shaped wood with two small square holes to represent windows and a larger rectangular hole to represent a door.
> take it

> take it
You pick up the dollhouse facade with both hands.
> x carriage

> x carriage
A baby carriage, consisting of a wicker bassinet -- furnished with pillow and blanket -- fixed atop a metal suspension frame with wheels.  Polly used to use this carriage when she played house, caring for Tomas as if he were her real baby and pushing him about the nursery.
> x mural

> x mural
A faded mural on the southern wall depicts a circus scene, jolly clowns and graceful acrobats and striking tigers cavorting in front of a rainbow-colored big top tent.
