> d

> d

You are in a foyer.
You can see a shoe cabinet and a bannister.
You can go up, west or south.
The foyer is a narrow passage with high lincrusta-embossed walls.  A low shoe cabinet is shoved against the wall next to the front door.  A narrow staircase, bordered by a walnut bannister, leads up to the second floor and a pair of pocket doors to the south lead to the parlour. The foyer continues to the west. To the east, you can see the house's front door; it is boarded up tight.

There is a china doll standing on the lowest stair of the staircase, her back to you.  But you immediately recognize her fine silk dress and her tight crown of pale lemon-yellow hair.

"Juliette? Is that you?" you ask.

The doll turns around.  It is indeed Juliette! You're shocked to see that her forehead is smashed open, her left eye missing and a large hole revealing the hollow interior of her head, but her right eye, a brilliant baby-blue, flashes when she sees you.  A smile of recognition spreads over her bone-white face. "Poppet! Oh I'm ever so glad to see you! I just knew you would wake up too!"

Juliette rushes forward and hugs you tightly, crushing your floppy cloth body against her hard bisque form.

"I'm glad to see you too," you say, "But what is going on? Where are the other toys?  And where is Polly?"

Juliette looks like she's about to burst into tears.  Looking her over, you suddenly notice a spiderweb of tiny cracks spread across her delicate face.  How can this be? Juliette is one of Polly's favorite toys! She would never let any harm come to Juliette...

"Oh Poppet, it's the most awful thing," says Juliette. "Polly is gone! I don't know how long, but I fear... I fear she has grown up!"

You feel suddenly light-headed, faint with terror. "No, no," you say, "You must be mistaken, Juliette! If Polly were grown up... then... how would we..."

You don't finish the thought.  You know Juliette must be right. It would explain so much.  The strange emptiness you feel, the decrepit state of the house... Of course the force that animates a doll like you would ebb quickly once your girl reached the age when she no longer played with dolls.  All dolls know that, understand that some day soon every doll must succumb to that eternal sleep just as surely as every human must someday shuffle off their mortal coil.  But... why are you back?  If Polly is gone, how could you still be awake?

"I know it's quite strange, Poppet," says Juliette. "I was ever so frightened as well when I woke up! I was sure that it couldn't last. But Poppet, I have such good news!  I have found a way to keep the magic alive!"

You blink.  That doesn't make any sense.  Everyone knows that, once a child is grown, there's no force strong enough to keep dolls awake.  "What is it?" you ask.

"Oh I shalln't be able to tell you just yet, Poppet," says Juliette with a merry laugh. "But when the time comes, I shall need you to help me. It shall be very important indeed that you follow my instructions or else none of us stay awake for much longer!"

"None of us? Are there others awake?" you ask.

Juliette nods but then she frowns.  "Yes... it's curious what the magic seems to affect.  Nevertheless, I know that together we can make it stick!  We shall talk again soon, Poppet, but for now I must attend to affairs. Tootles!"

She hops off the step and trundles off down the hallway, disappearing into the darkness.
