You can go west or north.
The parlour is a large room designed to entertain guests before dinner, but, with the curtains drawn and the windows boarded up, it has lost much of its former charm.  The heavy curtains and dark red walls combine to give the room an oppressive, stifling atmosphere and you almost feel like you're choking on the thick air as you enter the room... although you're not sure whether that's due to the dust in the air or to the psychological force of the room's dark shadows.  A high-backed divan sofa stands in the center of the room, facing a fireplace. A large oil painting hangs above the fireplace.

The foyer is to the north. The dining room is accessible to the west, through a pair of open pocket doors.
> x painting

> x painting
The painting depicts an older, regal-looking gentleman with big fluffy white dundrearies.  His leathery face is lined with wrinkles.  Of course, you recognize Grandfather immediately.  You can still hear his voice in your ear.

"Polly, what have you got there?"

"It's my dolly, Opa. Her name is Poppet."

She held you out to him and Grandfather took you, gently, in his leathery old hands and regarded you very closely as if you were something very important indeed. And then he handed you back to Polly with a chuckle.

"You like your Poppet, do you?"

"Oh yes, Opa. I love her."

"You know, Polly, this doll is magic."

"She's not, Grandfather," said Polly.  Polly was always a very serious girl who could tell when adults were patronizing her. "Poppet is just a dolly. Oma made her."

"Ah yes," said Grandfather, his eyes twinkling as if he knew some great secret that he was dying to impart. "Your grandmother is a remarkable woman with a needle and thread. But you're right.  Not even the most skilled seamstress can sew magic into a dolly. That only comes from a little girl's heart. When a girl loves a doll very much, that doll gets a little bit of magic in her, you see? I think you'll find your Poppet has more magic than you think."

The memory fades and you find yourself back in reality, alone in the cold, dark parlour.
> x divan

> x divan
An ornate high-backed divan sofa upholstered in worn button tufted leather. You notice a scrap of crumpled paper wedged between the cushions.
> read paper

