You are in a den.
You can see a taxidermy animal, a smoking chair, a fireplace, a bearskin rug and a deer heads.
You can go east.
Polly's Grandfather and guests would often retire to this room after dinner to talk and smoke pipes.  It was unspoken but generally understood that this was a space for men, so Polly rarely came in here.  But sometimes, when Grandfather was out, Polly would sneak in here for the illicit thrill of going into a forbidden place.  It is a cozy room, the walls lined with dark walnut bookshelves and a large plush smoking chair facing a marble fireplace.  A balding bearskin rug is draped before the hearth and taxidermied deer heads gaze down from the walls with their glass eyes.

Polly used to challenge herself to come into this room because the glassy stares of those taxidermy heads filled her with a delicious sense of terror. You remember that Polly was especially frightened by a full-body mount of some large black furry animal that Grandfather stationed above the mantle.

It's not there now.

You hear become aware of something rustling in the shadows, followed by a low wheezing, gasping sound: Breathing.
> x animal

> x animal
You have no idea what kind of animal this is.  You never saw its image identified in any of Polly's animal books and, if Polly's grandfather ever said what it was, you certainly don't remember now.  All you remember is that Polly used to have nightmares after seeing it mounted on Grandfather's shelf.  Its jet-black fur and broad, toothy maw haven't lost any of their ability to terrify.  Whatever force has given you life seems to have animated the creature as well; it's scuttling about the room, hissing and wheezing loudly, and keeping to the shadows.  Nevertheless, you can see a deep gash in its flank.  Its erratic movements have busted the brittle stitches down its side and the creature is leaking sawdust onto the floor.

It may be stuffed, but its claws, glistening in the dark, are very much real and very sharp.

> x chair

> x chair
A plush, overstuffed smoking chair, just perfect for curling up with a good book before a roaring fire.
> x fireplace

> x fireplace
A ornate marble fireplace, now scuffed and scratched until the stone has become dull and hazy. The hearth is clogged with piles of cold ashes.
> x rug

> x rug
The bearskin rug has lost much of its fur, revealing the leathery tanned pelt beneath.
> x heads

> x heads
Grandfather decorated his den with the mounted heads of deer and gazelles.  You're not sure whether they are trophies from his own hunts or just souvenirs that he bought on his travels.
> speak to animal

> speak to animal
You take a cautious step toward the creature.  "Hello? My name is Poppet. Do you... do you have a name?"

The creature snarls, a low rumbling noise deep in its throat.

"...Are you hurt?" you ask, eying the rip in the creature's flank. "Maybe I could help... Once I tore a seam when I was roughhousing with Birgitta and Polly sewed me back up good as new! I bet I could remember how she did it... if I just had the right tools..."

The creature snaps its jaws once, showing off pearly white urethane teeth.
> use needle on animal

> use needle on animal
"Please hold still," you say as you cautiously approach the animal.  You hold up the needle, indicating your intent.

The animal bristles, its black fur standing on end.

"I can fix you," you say, "Please let me help you.  You're losing sawdust."

The animal flexes and you can hear its claws tapping on the wooden floorboards. But it doesn't attack.

You're next to the beast now, close enough that you can feel the heat radiating off of it and smell the choking musk of its pelt.  You plunge the needle into the creature's side.  It does not react.  With a few deft motions, you quickly suture the wound.  There now!

As you complete your stitching, the creature releases a deep sigh, a sound like steam escaping, and is still.

"Is that better?" you ask.

The creature doesn't respond.  It has gone stiff, hunched back into the familiar threatening teeth-and-tongue bared pose that you remember seeing so many times before when Polly brought you into the den.  You're not sure how, but somehow treating the tear in its hide has caused the life to go right out of it.

You notice there's a small copper key shoved under the creature's apoxie sculpted tongue.  Huh!  Grandfather must have hidden it there.
> take copper key

> take copper key
You pluck the copper key from beneath the creature's apoxie sculpt tongue.
