You pull open the little drawers in the rolltop desk.  They're mostly empty, although one contains a small envelope.
> x envelope

> x envelope
A small sealed envelope.  Someone has written "Polly, Age 6" on it in swirly cursive handwriting.
> open envelope

> open envelope
You open it.
You tear open the envelope and find that it contains several small, yellowed teeth.  Tiny teeth.  Baby teeth, from the looks of it.  You wonder... were these Polly's teeth?  Did Grandfather save them as a memento of his granddaughter's fleeting childhood?

Polly... oh how you miss her!  Thinking about her makes your heart ache.  You wonder what became of her.  Did she grow up?  Did she live the life she always wanted?  Is she alive still, somewhere, today?  Or has too much time passed?

Overcome with emotion, you pocket the teeth.  You feel like you need to keep them close.

> x tome

> x tome
An old book with yellowed pages, bound in soft brown leather.  The title "Sorcery, Magicks & Fortune-Telling: Illustrated by Incantations, Specimens of Medical Magic, Anecdotes, Tales" is embossed on the cover.
> read tome

> read tome
The table of contents lists a number of strange and esoteric topics within this book:1. Charms to Cure Disorders of Grown People2. On the Creation of Poppets
3. On Charms to Block the Crossing of Thresholds4. On the Creation of Oracles5.Toads and Toad Lore6.Charms to Affect an Enemy's Perception7. Charms to Cure or Protect Children
8. Charms to Find Lost Objects  (To read a particular chapter, type "Ask Tome about [chapter number].")
> ask tome about 1

> ask tome about 1
"To cure a boil, one must slaughter a black hen, split it open, and lay it on the boil. To cure a headache, rub the patient's temples with vinegar. To cure sleeplessness, one must drink a draught of elderberries combined with one's mother's hair. To cure stomach pains, one must mix the patient's nail clippings with horse dung and expose the patient to the smoke when the mixture is burned."
> ask tome about 2

> ask tome about 2
"To make a poppet is one of the great works of deep magic.  Even an apprentice magus can easily learn to give inanimate objects the appearance of life --  to create a simulcrum that moves and even speaks as if it has inner life of its own is a simple matter of memorizing the right sloka and performing the proper ritual -- but to create a genuine poppet is trickier.  A poppet is formed when strong human emotions, such as anger, fear, or love, are focused upon a particular inanimate object.  That object eventually gains a form of limited sentience, so long as it remains in psychic proximity with the human who, perhaps unknowingly, created the poppet.  Otherwise, the poppet will "go to sleep" or, in effect, die."
> ask tome about 3

> ask tome about 3
"Concealed shoes hidden in the fabric of a building have been discovered in many European countries, as well as in other parts of the world, since at least the early modern period. The locations in which these shoes are typically found – such as stashed up chimneys – suggest that some may have been concealed as magical charms to prevent unnatural influences from crossing the threshold."
> ask tome about 4

> ask tome about 4
"Many alchemists and sorcerers have greatly desired to construct an oracle that could accurately foretell future events, because the usefulness of such a device would be beyond measure.  There are many different ways to learn of future events, from simple methods as the casting of bones to the apallingly dangerous xenoglossia.  But since the times of the ancients, the brazen head has remanied the preferred method, a spell by which a statue in the form of a human can answer questions put to it.  To construct such an oracle, it is necessary to combine chimney ashes, wild thyme, and the whiskers of a black cat in a matrix of kitchen grease. Smear the resulting mixture upon a statue or dummy in the image of a man -- or anything that has a mouth -- and it shall speak to you of the future."
> ask tome about 5

> ask tome about 5
"Toads are a frequent subject of the astute magus's attention, for these creatures are themselves magically imbued. Their dual nature, being creatures of both land and sea, makes them especially apt for our uses. The toad can by its mere presence bring bad luck upon a household, since it is the preferred form of the transformed warlock on the prowl to cause mischief.  To thwart such ill intentions, the magus must catch the toad, tie it to a pair of shears so as to imitate the posture of Our Lord upon the cross, and then consign it to the fire."
> ask tome about 6

> ask tome about 6
"The ability to deceive an enemy for one's own ends is of utmost value to the savvy magus, for a magus's enemies are many.  However, a magus may easily assume the form of another to elude his enemies by using the most basic principle of sympathethic magic. The magus must obtain some item of close personal significance to the one whose form he wishes to steal, some trinket or bauble will do nicely but a piece of the body, such as a lock of hair, will be best for this purpose. This item must be tied into a bundle with muslin fabric; as long as the magus possesses this charm, he will take on another's form in the eyes of his adversary. The effects of the spell, however, are limited only to the adversary; others will continue to see the magus in their true form."
> ask tome about 7

> ask tome about 7
"Children, having so recently passed into the world from the realms beyond, possess an innate understanding of the world as it truly is.  They instinctively feel the rythym of the deep magic which courses beneath the surface of reality, perhaps better than any trained magus.  However, this same affinity also makes them more suseptible to the workings of dark forces.  Every mother knows the secret charms to protect her child from any harm. The best charm to protect a child from any ill, no matter the source, is to fashion a necklace from bears' claws and children's teeth to be worn around the neck."
> ask tome about 8

> ask tome about 8
"Every person has that treasured object which has been lost to time, which she would dearly like to have returned to her clutches. To find that which has been lost, the spell-caster must place heliotrope blossoms or bay leaves under her pillow.  The next time that she sleeps, she will have a dream vision of the lost object."
