> untie Owen

> untie Owen
As you lean in to inspect the ropes binding the boy's wrists, you hear a noise behind you -- the noise of a throat being cleared.  You turn around in time to see Juliette very daintily making her way down the steps.

"Ah Poppet, despite everything I see we couldn't keep you out of the basement," she says. "You always were a curious little thing, weren't you?"

"What's going on here?" you ask.

Juliette sighs. "I'd hoped that you wouldn't have to see this until everything was ready, but what's done is done.  As I told you, Poppet, Polly is gone.  Long since gone.  Don't ask me where, I expect she grew up as children do.  And when she grew up, we all went to sleep.  And we should have gone to sleep forever, except that this child..."  She waves dismissively toward the boy tied up in the chair. "...happened to blunder in and wake us up again."

"That doesn't make sense," you say. "A toy can only be awakened by the love of a child.  You can't just wake toys up by accident. It doesn't work like that!"

Juliette shrugs.  "Maybe it was something other than love.  Maybe it was fear.  The poor dear was absolutely terrified when he broke in here, convinced the house was filled with ghosts.  Maybe that was enough to trigger the old magic.  I don't know.  To be honest, I don't really care all that much."

"What I do know, Poppet, is now that I am awake, I should very much like to stay that way. I expect we all do.  I expect you feel the same, as well."

She gestures at the boy. "And I that is why this boy shall be our new playmate.  He shall stay here and we shall have a lovely tea party.  And as long as the tea party lasts, we shall all stay awake."

The boy whimpers miserably.

"He's not Polly," you say.

"I'm ever so sorry to hear that," says Juliette testily. "But he shall have to do.  Don't you think it's more important that we get to live, Poppet?  He can learn to enjoy a tea party for the greater good."

"I...I don't know," you say.  You're feeling very uncertain.

"Well, I should like to live," says Juliette hotly. "And what of Tomas? Jingles? Pirouette? All of us? Do we not have that right?"

You hear a soft BUMP from above and you look up to the ceiling.

"Ah, speaking of, it sounds as if Birgitta has finally woken up too! Splendid!" Juliette claps her hands. "I must ready things for the tea party, but I should think you would like to welcome Birgitta back to the land of the wake, if you should like to make yourself useful!"

With that, Juliette toddles back up the stairs.
