> s

> s

You are in a nursery.
You can see a dollhouse, Birgitta and a carriage.
You can go north.
You recognize this room, it's Polly's nursery.  You couldn't count the happy hours that you spent here -- attending fancy tea parties with the other dolls, happily baking imaginary cakes in Polly's play oven, or just tidying the family rooms of Polly's giant dollhouse!  Now the nursery seems oddly quiet and still, the floor covered in a thick film of dust, the walls festooned with great gobs of cobwebs. A faded mural on the southern wall depicts a circus scene, jolly clowns and graceful acrobats and striking tigers cavorting in front of a rainbow-colored big top tent. You still see a few toys that you recognize, including Polly's old dollhouse, now broken and splintered, and, lying on the floor.  There are scuff marks in the dust that look like footprints.

Birgitta is lurching around the room, as if in a daze, bumping into furnishings and nearly tripping over her own feet.
> speak to Birgitta

> speak to Birgitta
"Birgitta? Are you okay?" you ask as you cautiously approach your old friend. "It's me, Poppet."

Birgitta turns suddenly to face you, her glass eyes rolling wildly in her head.  She can't seem to focus on you; it almost feels as if she's staring through you.

"Polly?  Where's Polly?  Polly is supposed to be here," she mutters, "I don't feel Polly.  Where is she?  Why isn't Polly here?"

"Polly is... gone," you say.  No sense in hiding the truth; Birgitta seems like she can already sense it. "I think she grew up.  But... good news, there's another child...."

'NO,NO."  Birgitta cuts you off, her voice loud and firm.  She grabs her head with her hands and moans loudly. "That's not right. That's not how it works."

"I know it's... strange.  But Juliette thinks that..."

"Nooo, no no," cries Birgitta. "That won't work! Why am I awake?! I shouldn't be awake! We shouldn't be awake!"

Birgitta buries her face in her hands and rocks back and forth on her heels, her moans growing louder and louder, rising to an animal crescendo.  You take a step backward, suddenly fearful.  What's going on? What's wrong with her?

"This isn't right! I don't...No no no!" cried Birgitta one last time before falling flat on her face and lying still.

You rush forward to help her but there's nothing you can do.  The life has gone right out of her; she's asleep again.  Perhaps forever.

You're not sure what just happened.  Did something go wrong?  Or did Birgitta choose this, choose to return to sleep rather than face a wakefulness without Polly?  You might never know.

