You are in a foyer.
You can see a shoe cabinet, a bannister and a Juliette.
You can go up, west or south.
The foyer is a narrow passage with high lincrusta-embossed walls.  A low shoe cabinet is shoved against the wall next to the front door.  A spiral staircase, bordered by a walnut bannister, leads up to the second floor and a pair of pocket doors to the south lead to the parlour. The foyer continues to the west. To the east, you can see the house's front door; it is boarded up tight.

You notice Juliette is waiting by the front door as you descend the stairs.

"Well? Did Birgitta wake up?" she asks.

"Yes," you say. "Yes.. for a little while.  I don't think..."

Juliette guesses what you're going to say from your expression.  "Oh Poppet, how sad!  I had so hoped that Birgitta would join us again.  But alas! I suppose she's made her choice and we'll have to respect that."

She fixes you with her one remaining eye.  Her stare is intense.  "Now Poppet, you might be feeling... ambivalent about this plan because of what happened to Birgitta.  You might even be thinking that we should release that boy in the cellar.  Rest assured, Poppet, that we cannot do that."

"I want this to be very clear, Poppet.  You can help us set up for our tea party, help us set up so that we can all have a good time and stay awake.  Or you can step aside and get out of the way.  But you will not release that boy, do you understand?  That would be the end for all of us... Jingles, Pirouette, me, you... The others have all agreed.  Are you with us, Poppet?"

"I...I..."

You're not sure what to say, but Juliette just fixes you with a glare.  "Go get the teapot in the cellar and bring it upstairs if you're ready to accept reality and join us. We're going to have a tea party."

You frown.  Are you ready to accept that?  If you let them keep the boy here, it does mean that you'll get to stay awake.  But if you let him go, that's the end of it for you... but is it right to keep him tied up? How long can humans even last in such a state?  Doesn't he have a home and a life of his own?  You guess you could go get the teapot if you're ready to accept Juliette's proposition... But... if not... there must be some way to let him go...
