You are in a basement.
You can see a teapot, boy, a hole and a toolbox.
You can go up.
The basement is an unfinished room of cold bare concrete. A single naked lightbulb dangling from the ceiling provides the only illumination, casting long shadows over the walls.  The packed dirt floor crunches under your feet as you step off the wooden slat stairs.  There's a hole in the way, right next to the door leading out of the basement.

There's a small folding table set up in the center of the room, ready for a tea party with a neatly pressed red-and-white tablecloth and a large porcelain teapot.  A young boy is tied up in a chair.
> put shoe in hole

> put shoe in hole
You drop the concealed shoe into the hole in the wall right by the door.  There!  This should prevent anyone from crossing the threshold into the basement.  No one's going to disturb you down here now.
> give necklace to boy

> give necklace to boy
The boy flinches nervously as you drape the necklace of animal claws and baby teeth around his neck, but then he relaxes almost immediately.  You can feel a change in the air and you're positive that he must feel it too.
> untie boy

> untie boy
You quickly untie the boy.  The ropes drop from his wrists and he's on his feet in a flash, so quickly that you're knocked to the ground.

He doesn't stop to thank you; he's immediately rushing at the windown in the corner, scrambling up the shelves and pushing his way out.

You can feel the air crackle in response as he scrabbles out through the window.  It's changed.  Whatever magic was keeping you upright must be gone now...

You're vaguely aware of fists pounding against the door upstairs, loud at first but gradually fading.  You're not sure if the pounding is getting softer or you're just fading out.  You're suddenly so sleepy that you don't have the strength to get to your feet.

This is it for you.  You're fading...  You have no regrets, though.  Whatever may come next, you know you did the right thing.  The boy didn't belong here.  You had no right to keep him and no expectation to stay awake.

Your last thoughts are of Polly.  How you miss her!  But you won't miss her for much longer.

That's your one consolation as you drift back to sleep.

Good night, Poppet.

